The first isolation of OROV in the Arinos area in Minas Gerais, Brazil, is of concern because this virus, under favorable ecologic conditions, can spread, and Oropouche fever may develop in the local people, who are susceptible to OROV. In fact, explosive Oropouche fever epidemics have been reported in all of the following areas in Brazil: Maranhão, Tocantins, Amazonas, Acre, Pará, and Rondônia States. Such epidemics have also been reported in Iquitos and Madre de Dios, Peru; and in Bejuco, Panama (
 
